===Etymology 1===
{{PIE root|en|lewbʰ}}
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{m|enm|love}}, {{m|enm|luve}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{m|ang|lufu||love, affection, desire}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*lubō||love}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*lewbʰ-||love, care, desire}}. Cognate with {{cog|ofs|luve||love}}, {{cog|goh|luba||love}}. Related to {{cog|ang|lēof||dear, beloved}}, {{m|ang|līefan||to allow, approve of}}, {{cog|is|ljúfur||dear; beloved; sweet; gentle}}, {{cog|stq|Ljoowe||love}}, {{cog|la|libet}}, {{m|la|lubō||to please}} and {{cog|sa|लुभ्यति|tr=lubhyati||to desire}}, {{cog|sq|lyp||to beg, ask insistently}}, {{m|sq|lips||to be demanded, needed}}, {{cog|sh|ljubiti}}, {{m|sh|ljubav}}, {{cog|ru|любо́вь}}, {{m|ru|люби́ть}}.

The closing-of-a-letter sense is presumably a truncation of ''With love'' or the like.

The verb is from {{etyl|enm|en}} {{m|enm|loven}}, {{m|enm|lovien}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{m|ang|lufian||to love, cherish, sow love to; fondle, caress; delight in, approve, practice}}, from the noun {{m|ang|lufu||love}}. See above. Compare {{cog|fy|leavje||to love}}, {{cog|de|lieben||to love}}, {{cog|is|lofa||to prize}} and {{m|is|loforð||a promise}}.

====Noun====
{{en-noun|~}}

# {{lb|en|uncountable}} Strong affection.
## A profound and caring [[affection]] towards someone.
##: {{ux|en|A mother’s '''love''' is not easily shaken.}}
##: {{ux|en|My husband’s '''love''' is the most important thing in my life.}}
##* {{w|John Milton}} (1608-1674)
##*: He on his side / Leaning half-raised, with looks of cordial '''love''' / Hung over her enamoured.
## A feeling of intense [[attraction]] towards someone.
##: {{ux|en|I have never been in '''love''' as much as I have with you.}}
##* {{quote-book|year=1898|author={{w|Winston Churchill (novelist)|Winston Churchill}}
|title={{w|The Celebrity}}|chapter=8
|passage=The humor of my proposition appealed more strongly to Miss Trevor than I had looked for, and from that time forward she became her old self again; for, even after she had conquered her '''love''' for the Celebrity, the mortification of having been jilted by him remained.}}
## A profound feeling of [[trust]] and [[security]] towards a person or a [[deity]].
## A feeling of [[care]] and [[mercy]] towards people or living beings in general.
## A deep or abiding [[liking]] for something.
##: {{ux|en|My '''love''' of cricket knows no bounds.}}
# {{lb|en|countable}} The object of one’s romantic feelings; a [[darling]] or [[sweetheart]].
#: {{ux|en|I met my '''love''' by the gasworks wall.}}
#* {{w|Edmund Spenser}} (c.1552–1599)
#*: Open the temple gates unto my '''love'''.
# {{lb|en|colloquial|British}} {{non-gloss definition|A term of friendly address, regardless of feelings.}}
#: {{ux|en|Hello '''love''', how can I help you?}}
# {{lb|en|euphemistic}} A sexual desire; sexual activity.
#* 1986, Ben Elton & al., ''[[w:Blackadder II|Blackadder II]]'', "[[w:Bells (Blackadder)|Bells]]":
#*:—What think you, my lord, of... '''love'''?
#*:—You mean ‘[[rumpy-pumpy]]’.
# {{non-gloss definition|Used as the [[closing]], before the [[signature]], of a [[letter]], especially between good friends or family members, or by the young.}}
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} A thin [[silk]] [[material]].
#* '''1664''', {{w|Robert Boyle}}, ''Experiments and Considerations Touching Colours,{{...}}''
#*: Such a kind of transparency, as that of a Sive, a piece of Cyprus, or a '''Love'''-Hood.
# A [[climb]]ing [[plant]], ''[[Clematis vitalba]]''.

